Author: FXGalvatron#0569
Content:
Okay, so. If you're like me and super clueless about the kinds of jobs available after completing this degree, here are some. There are many, many roles and it is highly recommended that everyone update their LinkedIn Profile to get some internships that you might be interested in. Here are some job roles and there are so many more available abroad. Optimize your profile so that recruiters reach out to you, do some certifications (preferably CS-sided because afaik, most recruiters tend to look for good CSE certifications and will give you an advantage over other candidates, I dunno any EEE certifications, sorry) and do some projects to make sure your profile stands out.

Here are some job positions in EEE available in Chennai.
https://www.linkedin.com/jobs/search/?geoId=115702354&keywords=electrical%20engineer&location=Chennai%2C%20Tamil%20Nadu%2C%20India

Here are some internships:
https://www.linkedin.com/jobs/search/?f_E=1&geoId=115702354&keywords=electrical%20engineer&location=Chennai%2C%20Tamil%20Nadu%2C%20India

Good luck y'all! College is ending soon! (Only one year because 4th year won't be much I think, correct me if I am wrong. Mostly projkect work only.)

Author: FXGalvatron#0569
Content:
If anyone wants to learn Python (like an intro course), I highly recommend CS50P. There's a variation called CS50X which teaches people (almost) everything there is to know aboyt programming. :))

Link for both- 

CS50P:- https://cs50.harvard.edu/python/2022/
CS50X:- https://www.edx.org/course/introduction-computer-science-harvardx-cs50x

This one's from Georgia Tech for Python as well.
https://www.edx.org/professional-certificate/introduction-to-python-programming

If you need any CSE related courses, lmk and I'd be more than happy to hook you guys up with thiose (as I am looming to transition from EEE to CSE, I am always on the lookout for great (and FREE) resources!)
